TWEET: Being an overthinker is one of the most painful experiences a person can have. It's a life of constant imagination that never comes true. Don't torture yourself. Start taking advantage of opportunities to create a better future. NOW!
REPLY: What people call "overthinking" is usually a loop.
A question arises, but the mind keeps generating possibilities instead of settling on one. The same thoughts repeat.
The exit is nirṇaya: decide—and act. Action closes the question and breaks the loop.

---

TWEET: The Hindu views man as a manifestation of the impersonal Brahman, without individual self.
REPLY: Not exactly. The Upaniṣads don't deny the self; they identify it with Brahman.
The claim is not "no individual self," but that the deepest self (Ātman) is not separate from Brahman.

---

TWEET: Old memories, hurts, fears, angers, resentments, etc., can arise in meditation. Simply allow them to arise without resisting, analyzing, judging, or denying them. Just watch them without getting involved.
REPLY: Vedic tradition calls these vāsanās: latent impressions accumulated through experience.
Meditation doesn't create them, only exposes them.
Seeing them without identification gradually dissolves them.

---

TWEET: i had a weird experience while meditating where my brain opened a new brain to think about things while my first brain kept meditating
REPLY: What you're describing sounds close to what Vedic tradition calls sākṣī (the witness).
Meditation continues, while thoughts appear in another layer of the mind.
For a moment the observer and the thinking process stop being the same thing.
It can feel like two minds.

---

TWEET: The most powerful position is needing nothing. Every attachment is a lever someone else can pull.
REPLY: ईशावास्यमिदं सर्वं यत्किञ्च जगत्यां जगत्
तेन त्यक्तेन भुञ्जीथा मा गृधः कस्यस्विद्धनम्

Tena tyaktena bhuñjīthā — enjoy through renunciation. Do not grasp or covet.
That is the only position no one can leverage.

